description:
There is an increasing need for standardisation of bioassay metadata into machine-readable formats to enhance the reproducibility and usability of bioassays in antimicrobial resistance-associated drug discovery and development. At the study result output level, general ontologies such as the BioAssay Ontology (BAO) already exists, but antibacterial drug discovery-specific ontologies that can aid in the standardisation process at the protocol level are missing. This poster presents results from testing 10 existing experimental assay-specific ontologies within this project to check the extent of extraction of information from natural language processing (NLP) models. But none of them were able to provide a complete overview of the underlying information. 
 About the COMBINE Bioassay Protocol Ontology (BPO)&nbsp; 
 The  COMBINE Bioassay Protocol Ontology (BPO)  presented in this poster was initially established in order to extend the interoperability and reusability of in-vivo AMR bioassay protocol data generated within COMBINE. &nbsp;BPO was constructed with the help of ontology creation tools like ROBOT (http://robot.obolibrary.org/) and the Ontology Development Kit ODK (https://github.com/INCATools/ontology-development-kit) to programmatically develop the ontology. 
 We created an application ontology through the combination of existing terms from prominent ontologies such as NCBI Taxonomy and PATO, along with new terms around the animal model-specific details, such as mouse inbred and outbred status. Alongside the addition of new terms, several terms have been requested to the parent reference ontologies. Overall, the BPO ontology presented in this poster has 209 classes and 2,242 axioms. 
 After the poster was presented, the  IMI-funded COMBINE project  proceeded to integrate the BPO into the GRIT42 information retrieval environment for protocol-level annotation of bioassays. 
 Download and use the BPO, GRIT42 Software &amp; COMBINE data 

 The  BPO is available for download through GitHub  
 The&nbsp; Open Access GRIT42 software  is available for use. 
 Data from the IMI COMBINE&nbsp; Multicenter Study to Standardize a Mouse Pneumonia Model with Pseudomonas aeruginosa and Klebsiella pneumoniae for Antibiotic Development  has also been made available for download via Zenodo. 

 &nbsp; 
